NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Play: I think Shirley took a reasonable line. The diamonds were very unfavorable, however. Another way to play the diamonds is to take 2 finesses against Ben. Say she leads the @D9 intending to duck if Ben plays low. Even if that loses to the @DJ, she can take another diamond finesse and will take 3 diamond tricks any time Ben has at least one honor which will happen 75% of the time. Half the time the honors will be split, and 25% of the time Ben will hold both honors.|
PG| ***** 60 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Granted if Margaret had Ben's diamond honors then the play I suggested would lose 2 tricks. Playing the way Shirley played, when Margaret played a low diamond at the 2nd diamond trick, she would have to guess whether to put up the @DQ or @D9. Playing the diamonds the way I suggested eliminates any guessing, but she was still unlucky.|
PG| ***** 61 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Another thing to note was Ben's very nice heart play. That is an expert's trick. Whenever you see KJ on the table and you hold the Ace behind dummy as on this hand you should lead low. Declarer has to guess what to do and will often guess wrong when your partner holds the Q. And if declarer holds the Q your play does not matter. It is either a good deceptive play or it makes no difference at worst.|
PG| ***** 62 ***** |


NT|^B@2
nome: When it goes 1 minor-P and the responder has 6-9 HCP and no 4-card major but has 4 or 5 card minors, is there a rule of thumb when to bid 3 of the minor and when to bid 1N?|
PG| ***** 63 ***** |


cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|With 5 cards in the minor I tend to jump to 3 (assuming you are playing inverted minors). With 4 cards in the minor and no 4-card major, as Shirley had, I sometimes have to jump to 3 also.|
PG| ***** 64 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|At times, with 4-cards in the minor, and no 4-card major, and 6-9 you have to bid 1NT which I don't like to do. However, over 1@C, if you are exactly 3-3-3-4 (e.g clubs is your only 4 card suit) if you have 6 or 7, many experts (including me when partner agrees) will bid 1@D with their 3 card suit just to avoid having to bid 1NT. That way they play 1C-P-1NT shows 8-10 which works out much better.|
