^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Bidding: Obviously you can't open a weak 2 in clubs so if you want to preempt with a 6-card club suit you have to open 3@C. That 3@C is sometimes done with a 6-card suit. However, you need to have a good reason to open 3C with a 6-card suit. 3rd seat is always a good reason. 2nd seat is a negative against opening with a 6 card suit. In general, your 2nd seat preempts should be relatively disciplined.|
PG| ***** 85 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Nevertheless, you certainly should preempt in 2nd seat when you have the appropriate hand, but 2nd seat is the hand where the preempt is not as likely to work. The reason is because partner is more likely to have a good hand and a preempt may preempt partner rather than the opponents. Why is partner more likely to have a good hand? because 1st seat has passed, showing a relatively weak hand.|
PG| ***** 86 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If you have a weak hand, that means 3rd and 4th seats hold a majority of the points and since partner is 4th seat, he is more likely to have a good hand. So you need to be a bit more careful in 2nd seat. although, having said that I would still open 3@C in 2nd seat at this vul because I am not vul, I am short in the majors (making it likely that the opponents have a major suit fit).|
PG| ***** 87 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Preempting has a lot of upside going for it and despite the fact that, if I were Margaret I would be annoyed at partner for ruining my nice hand, the preempt still worked well.|
PG| ***** 88 ***** |


NT|^B@2
ladydoc: Would you bid with Ben's hand? I would have passed.|
PG| ***** 89 ***** |


cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Absolutely I would bid 3NT. If he passes, the opponents are likely to be stealing the hand. Bidding against preempts is a matter of playing the odds. You no longer have room to explore.|
PG| ***** 90 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So you have to make bids that are going to work out more often than not. Basically you are now playing the odds. And sometimes you are going to get burned. But you are going to get burned more often if you pass and play scared bridge. I love playing against timid opponents when I preempt.|
PG| ***** 91 ***** |


